<article class="content-card">
  <h2>About Heatwaves</h2>
  <p>
    A heatwave is a period of unusually high temperatures that pose serious health risks.
    India‚Äôs northwestern, central, and eastern regions‚Äîespecially Delhi, Rajasthan, Punjab, UP, and Bihar‚Äîface extreme heatwaves during summer.
  </p>
  <p>
    Heatwaves can cause dehydration, fainting, heat exhaustion, and life-threatening heatstroke.
  </p>
</article>

<!-- WARNING SIGNS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Warning Signs of Heat Illness</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Extreme tiredness and dizziness</li>
    <li>Headache and nausea</li>
    <li>Fast heartbeat</li>
    <li>Hot, dry skin or heavy sweating</li>
    <li>Confusion, fainting (sign of heatstroke)</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- PREPAREDNESS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Preparedness Before Heatwave Season</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Stay hydrated ‚Äî drink water frequently.</li>
    <li>Store ORS (Oral Rehydration Solution) at home.</li>
    <li>Keep rooms cool using fans, curtains, and ventilation.</li>
    <li>Wear light, loose cotton clothing.</li>
    <li>Avoid outdoor activities from 12 PM to 4 PM.</li>
    <li>Check IMD heatwave alerts regularly.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- DOs & DON‚ÄôTs -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Do‚Äôs & Don‚Äôts During a Heatwave</h2>

  <h3>‚úî Do‚Äôs</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Drink water and ORS throughout the day.</li>
    <li>Carry a water bottle while traveling.</li>
    <li>Cover head with a cap or cloth when going outside.</li>
    <li>Keep elderly, children, and pets indoors.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>‚ùå Don‚Äôts</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Do NOT go out during peak afternoon hours.</li>
    <li>Do NOT drink alcohol or caffeinated drinks.</li>
    <li>Do NOT leave children in parked vehicles.</li>
    <li>Do NOT eat stale or spoiled food.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- FIRST AID -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>First Aid for Heatstroke</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Move the person to a cool, shaded area.</li>
    <li>Loosen clothes and help them lie down.</li>
    <li>Give water OR ORS if they are conscious.</li>
    <li>Apply cool cloths on neck, armpits, and forehead.</li>
    <li>Call emergency services immediately.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- HELPING OTHERS -->
